<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/88C5F7F9-8DCC-41C9-BC4F-F37DA01075C7"><gtr:id>88C5F7F9-8DCC-41C9-BC4F-F37DA01075C7</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of East Anglia</gtr:name><gtr:department>International Development</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Earlham Road</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Norwich</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Norfolk</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>NR4 7TJ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/88C5F7F9-8DCC-41C9-BC4F-F37DA01075C7"><gtr:id>88C5F7F9-8DCC-41C9-BC4F-F37DA01075C7</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of East Anglia</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Earlham Road</gtr:line1><gtr:line4>Norwich</gtr:line4><gtr:line5>Norfolk</gtr:line5><gtr:postCode>NR4 7TJ</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>East of England</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/91C27C5A-D7B3-4E3C-B981-9BDFA10FA6BA"><gtr:id>91C27C5A-D7B3-4E3C-B981-9BDFA10FA6BA</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Paul</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Philip</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Clist</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FI021353%2F1"><gtr:id>7B1A750D-19CE-43D6-82DC-6E40705F5BC7</gtr:id><gtr:title>Aid Allocation, Composition and Effect</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/I021353/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Donors choose to give development aid to poorer countries around the world. Even when other budgets are cut, the UK government is sticking to the target of aid representing 0.7 per cent of British GDP. But how do donors decide who to give this aid to? Is poverty more important than trade links for a given donor? Is a common colonial past a less important factor in recent years? Do donors reward good recipient policy?&lt;br />&lt;br />Dr Clist's work builds on existing empirical work to help answer these questions, looking at a number of major aid donors. An early result of this research is that donors do not reward good policy, a finding that contradicts other recent research. Instead, it is shown that donors practice pragmatic selectivity - in response to different levels recipient policy and governance donors do not alter the amount of aid but the type. Dr Clist will explore the reasons for this, including the idea of the Samaritan impulse - the inability to withhold aid from poorer countries. The research is predominately empirical, but also utilises economic modelling.&lt;br />&lt;br />For further details, see: &lt;a href=&quot;https://sites.google.com/site/paulclist/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;>https://sites.google.com/site/paulclist/&lt;/a>&lt;/p>

&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

