&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2013-01-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-02-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>146194</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>1. My work on aid and tax has had a lasting impact. 
* It was cited in &amp;quot;The Economic Impact and Effectiveness of Development Aid - Economic Affairs Committee Report&amp;quot;, chapter 4 (see http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201012/ldselect/ldeconaf/278/27807.htm)
* It has been influential in the International Center for Taxation and Development new dataset, and related conference in Washington DC in September 2014, where IMF researchers have engaged to discuss data quality issues. 

2. My work on aid allocation has been part of the conversation on how development aid should be best used in the current economic climate. For example, it was cited by Andy Sumner's work on the new bottom billion, which has been influential in thinking about DFID's aid to India. 

3. It has established me as an expert on development aid, which has led to significant policy influence with regards Payment by Results.</gtr:description><gtr:id>B528FE06-E69E-40EF-9EB8-BED558EF775E</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>5437dbcc171233.97028959</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>1. Aid is not negatively associated with tax revenues, even when given as aid grants. 2. Development aid is not allocated on the basis of good governance: Poverty, Population and Proximity are much more important than Policy. 3. Donors do, however, alter the type of aid in response to governance, by giving more control to recipients with better policy environments.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The top two publications each have over 25 citations. They have contributed to the policy conversations over how development aid should be best spent, and in what form.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>083815A6-0EB0-4152-B8DD-1DAD75478170</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>r-8202723048.816177b2f31c10</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>5C3D7D1A-68D6-44A0-9DF9-DF8FDA4D56F9</gtr:id><gtr:title>Foreign aid and domestic taxation: multiple sources, one conclusion</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Development Policy Review</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/b15df3a5e2339916e15f0dcea7feae00"><gtr:id>b15df3a5e2339916e15f0dcea7feae00</gtr:id><gtr:othe